    recommendation: 'Spend your first few sessions at a beginner-friendly break with spread-out crowds. Learn to read priority before you attempt a busy lineup. If you do drop in on someone, apologize immediately and paddle over — most surfers respect an honest mistake.',
    faq: [
      { q: 'What is dropping in?', a: 'Dropping in means paddling for and riding a wave that another surfer already has priority on. It is dangerous and disrespectful. The surfer closest to the peak owns the wave; anyone else must pull off.' },
      { q: 'What is snaking?', a: 'Snaking is paddling around another surfer who is already in position for a wave so that you end up closer to the peak. It is considered extremely poor etiquette and can lead to confrontation.' },
      { q: 'Can beginners surf at crowded breaks?', a: 'Yes, but stay in the white water zone away from the peak. Do not paddle into the main takeoff area until you can consistently catch waves and control your direction. Crowded lineups require experience to navigate safely.' },
      { q: 'How do I apologize in the water?', a: 'A simple wave, smile, and "my bad" or "sorry" works. Acknowledge the mistake and paddle away from the person. Surfers are generally forgiving of honest errors, especially if you are clearly learning.' },
      { q: 'What should I do if someone drops in on me?', a: 'If it is a clear drop-in, shout "wave" or "hey" to alert them. If they catch it by accident and apologize, let it go. If someone repeatedly drops in, paddle over and politely explain priority. Avoid confrontations.' },
    ],
